description.plain: Passenger aka Mike Rosenberg is a multi award winning, platinum selling singer-songwriter from Brighton, UK. His career so far has spanned over a decade and taken him on a journey that has seen him travel multiple times around the globe playing street corners to stadiums and headlining some of the most iconic venues and stages. He is most synonymous with the hugely successful song ‘Let Her Go’ that has been viewed on You Tube over 2 billion times, is approaching 1 billion streams on Spotify and has reached number 1 in 19 x countries. This is however only one side of Passenger and there is an incredible body of work behind the humble troubadour. The latest album is his 13th studio album in 12 x years. Recorded at the iconic Abbey Rd studios and Mike’s own studio in Brighton, it sees him record with a string quartet for the first time and is a beautiful and resonate testament to his time on the streets of Britain.

songs.full_title: Let Her Go by Passenger
songs.title: Let Her Go

description.plain:
“Let Her Go” was released in July 2012, the second single from Passenger’s third album, All the Little Lights. It achieved international success, topped many charts around the world, and sold well: over a million digital copies in the UK and more than 4 million in the US.

Of the song’s success, Passenger told Elle “I can’t really explain how much of a shock it was.”  The aspiring sing-songwriter had spent five years busking,

playing street gigs, and traveling around making no money at all; playing at tiny venues and tiny pubs around Europe and Australia. So it wasn’t even in my universe for it to happen. It didn’t even feel possible for me to have a song on the radio, let alone something that was going to turn into this absolute sort of global monster. So it was such a flipping shock.

“Let Her Go” has been described as a melancholic song, with somber lyrics that redouble the moody affect of the main instrumentals, a soft acoustic guitar.

The song was famously featured in a 2014 Budweiser commercial that aired during Super Bowl XLVIII, which depicted a puppy with a  preference for the iconic Bud Clydesdales to his human owners. It was used also in the Season 7 finale of CBC’s Heartland.

songs.full_title: Hell Or High Water by Passenger
songs.title: Hell Or High Water

description.plain:
Besides wondering whether their relationship was troubled from the start before their break-up. Troubles that was unknown to him and he still had not realised. Passenger questioned if it’s already too late to save what they had. Despite everything, he was still trying to cling onto this relationship and wanted to know if there’s still anything left for him to do to turn this whole thing around.

As someone who deeply longed for love and had waited a long time for it to come (Verse 1), believing the girl he was in a relationship with to be “the one”, she finally left – fading into the night was brutal, but also confusing for him. This thirst for affection and love was unrelenting despite her departure, as well as the remnants of his feelings for her were still alive. And as shown several times in the final bridge verses, he was in denial that it was truly over and still trying to justify their failed relationship with questions he hoped that could be answered the way he wanted them to be.

The entire song, really, was two question marks: “Why was it broken?” and “Could it be fixed?”. But even at the end of his pondering – and the end of the song – they were still unanswered. But still, what’s done was already done, and their hearts were already broken in the first place.
